Jeff Wicks, News24Johannesburg &ndash; Here are some of the most important figures from the National Senior Certificate results announced in Midrand on Wednesday night:Get your matric results on News24&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The 2016 matric pass rate increased to 72.5% - 1.8 percentage points more than last year&rsquo;s rate of 70.7% (including progressed pupils); &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Without the progressed pupils, the pass rate was 76.2%, up from 74% in 2015; &bull; &nbsp; &nbsp;More than 108 000 pupils who who sat for examinations had been progressed; &bull; &nbsp; &nbsp;Of the 674 652 pupils who registered, 64 474 did not write the exams; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The Free State was the best-performing province with a 93.2% pass rate, excluding progressed learners; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The Eastern Cape remained the worst-performing province with a 63.3% pass rate; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;111 schools obtained a 100% pass rate; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;18 schools recorded a 0% pass rate; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Gauteng and KwaZulu-Natal were the leading provinces when it comes to bachelor's passes; &bull; &nbsp; &nbsp;The number of distinctions achieved was 158 166 - an increase of more than 65 000 compared to 2015; &bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;54% of the country's matrics came from the three worst performing provinces: the Eastern Cape, Limpopo, and KwaZulu-Natal.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.